WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Hi, my name's Matt and I'm Head of Foresight and Insight at the British Red Cross.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:17.559
Cast your mind back to March of 2020, what now feels like several lifetimes ago.

00:00:17.559 --> 00:00:22.879
The COVID-19 pandemic was starting to grip the world and the UK, where I am, was entering

00:00:22.879 --> 00:00:25.280
its first national lockdown.

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:29.700
The British Red Cross was in the midst of planning our emergency response.

00:00:29.700 --> 00:00:34.619
We were gearing up to deliver food parcels and deliver medicines, support people who

00:00:34.619 --> 00:00:41.779
were lonely or socially isolated, and help people who had been moved into emergency accommodation.

00:00:41.779 --> 00:00:48.700
But how did we know who needed support and where we might find them?

00:00:48.700 --> 00:00:53.500
The day before lockdown began, I made our first Git commit to what would become known

00:00:53.500 --> 00:00:56.500
as the Vulnerability Index.

00:00:56.500 --> 00:01:02.139
My colleague Elle and I were rapidly designing a map to model vulnerability to COVID-19

00:01:02.139 --> 00:01:05.260
in neighbourhoods across the UK.

00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:10.940
This map would be used to plan not only the British Red Cross's pandemic response, but

00:01:10.940 --> 00:01:17.820
would also inform other voluntary and community sector organisations, as well as government

00:01:17.820 --> 00:01:21.059
and public health bodies.

00:01:21.059 --> 00:01:29.019
It needed to be expansive, rigorous, and accurate, and we needed to build it quickly.

00:01:29.019 --> 00:01:36.379
700 commits, more than 100 data indicators, and several new grey hairs later, this is

00:01:36.379 --> 00:01:38.580
where we are now.

00:01:38.580 --> 00:01:43.739
My team and I built a set of open source tools that measured the vulnerability of different

00:01:43.739 --> 00:01:48.339
geographical areas of the UK and their ability to cope.

00:01:48.339 --> 00:01:54.339
Today we have a suite of dashboards, maps, and datasets that anyone can use for free.

00:01:54.339 --> 00:01:57.059
How did we get there?

00:01:57.059 --> 00:02:01.699
We had to figure out what makes people vulnerable to the disease.

00:02:01.699 --> 00:02:09.100
COVID-19 isn't just a public health emergency, it's also a social and economic emergency,

00:02:09.100 --> 00:02:14.559
and we needed to account for vulnerability in a multidimensional way.

00:02:14.559 --> 00:02:21.880
We gathered data on over 100 indicators related to people's clinical vulnerability and socioeconomic

00:02:21.880 --> 00:02:28.179
vulnerability, as well as their wider health and wellbeing needs, but we had to find some

00:02:28.179 --> 00:02:35.559
way to merge everything into a single vulnerability score, and we needed to do it fast.

00:02:35.559 --> 00:02:38.559
So I picked up the phone and I called Mike.

00:02:38.559 --> 00:02:44.000
Hey, I'm Mike, a data scientist at the British Red Cross.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:47.759
After agreeing to redeploy into Matt's team, I took a quick peek at the repositories he

00:02:47.759 --> 00:02:51.559
had created, excited to see what I might be working on.

00:02:51.559 --> 00:02:57.880
My reaction was, of course, panic.

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:02.919
What I thought was going to be a project in its infancy had already morphed into thousands

00:03:02.919 --> 00:03:07.720
of lines of code, split across hundreds of files, datasets, and repositories.

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:12.320
Add to this the pressure of a pandemic and the need to develop rapidly, I wondered what

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:13.320
I got myself into.

00:03:13.320 --> 00:03:18.800
Thankfully, I was soon to learn that these feelings of panic were unfounded.

00:03:18.800 --> 00:03:21.919
The project had a silent hero working in the background that allowed me to quickly get

00:03:21.919 --> 00:03:23.479
up to speed.

00:03:23.479 --> 00:03:27.960
This hero was the Tidyverse.

00:03:27.960 --> 00:03:30.880
So why the Tidyverse?

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:34.800
Every data science problem presents a unique landscape which must be navigated.

00:03:34.800 --> 00:03:39.199
Here at the British Red Cross, we like to think of the Tidyverse as the cognitive superhighway

00:03:39.199 --> 00:03:41.479
through many of these landscapes.

00:03:41.479 --> 00:03:45.119
The signs are clear and easy to follow, and it's easy to show colleagues and your future

00:03:45.119 --> 00:03:48.039
self how to navigate back through the terrain.

00:03:48.039 --> 00:03:54.440
But this is not to say the Tidyverse is always the correct path to take for every problem.

00:03:54.440 --> 00:03:58.240
Depending upon the task at hand, other tools and paradigms may be better suited, such as

00:03:58.240 --> 00:03:59.240
Pandas and Datatable.

00:03:59.240 --> 00:04:04.160
However, at the British Red Cross, we often have a requirement to develop and collaborate

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:08.679
quickly, and this is where we believe the Tidyverse shines most brightly.

00:04:08.679 --> 00:04:15.240
It quickly allows us to translate our ideas to code.

00:04:15.240 --> 00:04:19.760
This is because the unifying design principles of the Tidyverse are centred first and foremost

00:04:19.760 --> 00:04:25.160
around cognitive performance, not computational performance.

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:29.160
To demonstrate why this is important, I'm going to show you some example code snippets

00:04:29.160 --> 00:04:32.519
from the vulnerability index Matt introduced earlier.

00:04:32.519 --> 00:04:37.119
For each snippet, I'll demonstrate how the unifying principles of the Tidyverse make

00:04:37.119 --> 00:04:43.079
development quicker and easier, allowing us to respond rapidly to the emerging pandemic.

00:04:43.079 --> 00:04:48.760
First, let's take a look at the human-centred and inclusive principles.

00:04:48.760 --> 00:04:53.519
Together, they acknowledge that data scientists come in all shapes and sizes.

00:04:53.519 --> 00:04:58.239
This means the Tidyverse APIs and documentation are designed to be read and written by everyone,

00:04:58.239 --> 00:05:00.399
irrespective of their background.

00:05:00.399 --> 00:05:04.399
This means it's not just for computer science graduates whose idea of a fun weekend is arguing

00:05:04.399 --> 00:05:10.359
about whether a rate should be 0 or 1 indexed.

00:05:10.359 --> 00:05:15.880
This quote from the Tidyverse design principles book sums up the human and inclusive principles

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:18.320
nicely.

00:05:18.320 --> 00:05:23.440
One particularly powerful idea is that of affordance, the exterior of a tool, so suggest

00:05:23.440 --> 00:05:26.399
how to use it.

00:05:26.399 --> 00:05:31.440
For example, take a look at this code snippet written by Matt that calculates a mean total

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:43.440
response time from the fire and rescue authorities using a classic dplyr-style pipeline.

00:05:43.440 --> 00:05:47.119
Without ever having seen the code, and only a little bit of prior Tidyverse knowledge,

00:05:47.119 --> 00:05:52.220
it's quick to read and intuitive to understand what is going on.

00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:58.279
Take the fire and rescue authority stats, filter only for fires in English dwellings

00:05:58.279 --> 00:06:04.079
and create a new variable called year, select only the variables of interest, and finally,

00:06:04.079 --> 00:06:08.600
group by a geographical variable to find the average 3-year fire and rescue response time

00:06:08.600 --> 00:06:11.720
in a given area.

00:06:11.720 --> 00:06:16.079
The code almost reads like English prose, listing off a set of clear instructions.

00:06:16.079 --> 00:06:19.720
There is no requirement to reason about things that computers are optimized to do, such as

00:06:19.720 --> 00:06:21.799
indexing and subsetting.

00:06:21.799 --> 00:06:25.760
The result is code that is quicker to write, read, and collaborate on.

00:06:25.760 --> 00:06:30.679
Another important design principle of the Tidyverse is that of consistency.

00:06:30.679 --> 00:06:35.160
Principally, this idea means finding the smallest possible set of key ideas and using

00:06:35.160 --> 00:06:37.440
them again and again.

00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:44.000
This manifests itself in two ways in the Tidyverse, in data structures and in function APIs.

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.000
The code snippet I'm about to show demonstrates the power of this idea effectively.

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:52.839
This code generates a data frame of weights across four domains of vulnerability where

00:06:52.839 --> 00:06:56.920
only two domains should be weighted at any given time, and the sum of the weights must

00:06:56.920 --> 00:06:57.920
equal one.

00:06:57.920 --> 00:07:03.119
The main power of this snippet lies in the first function, crossing, which generates

00:07:03.119 --> 00:07:07.239
all combinations of variables found in the dataset while de-duplicating and sorting the

00:07:07.239 --> 00:07:09.959
inputs.

00:07:09.959 --> 00:07:16.880
Here, the yellow arrows demonstrate the consistent tidy data frame structures used throughout

00:07:16.880 --> 00:07:19.320
this example.

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:23.679
Using one common data structure over and over again reduced the cognitive load required

00:07:23.679 --> 00:07:27.440
to reason about the problem we were challenged with.

00:07:27.440 --> 00:07:32.059
One reason for this is that the consistent data structures mean the APIs of the Tidyverse

00:07:32.059 --> 00:07:38.600
communicate seamlessly.

00:07:38.600 --> 00:07:43.359
For example, we can see here how the functions from TidyR and BplyR fit together like Lego

00:07:43.359 --> 00:07:44.359
blocks.

00:07:44.359 --> 00:07:47.720
This mostly removes the need to reason about the input and output structure of the data

00:07:47.720 --> 00:07:55.200
being passed throughout the Tidyverse, making it quick to learn new tidy functions and packages.

00:07:55.200 --> 00:07:58.679
Consistency also extends to the naming of functions throughout the Tidyverse.

00:07:58.679 --> 00:08:02.880
In general, Tidyverse function names offer imperative verbs over nouns, long names over

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:06.920
short names, and thematic unity between similar groups of functions.

00:08:06.920 --> 00:08:10.079
The end result are functions that are easier to remember and implement.

00:08:10.079 --> 00:08:14.679
For this particular code snippet, I recall a deep sense of joy as I intuitively knew

00:08:14.679 --> 00:08:18.920
the name of the functions I needed to recall, despite only using several of them a handful

00:08:18.920 --> 00:08:19.920
of times.

00:08:19.920 --> 00:08:23.799
The final design principle of the Tidyverse is that it should be composable.

00:08:23.799 --> 00:08:28.040
This means that complex problems should be solved by combining many smaller pieces, with

00:08:28.040 --> 00:08:30.559
each smaller piece easy to reason about.

00:08:30.559 --> 00:08:34.880
This is realised in the Tidyverse for a predominant functional programming paradigm that uses

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:36.599
immutable objects.

00:08:36.599 --> 00:08:40.719
This means problems are solved by combining functions that transform data, rather than

00:08:40.719 --> 00:08:44.679
by creating objects whose state changes over time.

00:08:44.679 --> 00:08:48.200
We saw the power of this idea previously, where a consistent immutable Tidy DataFrame

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:50.239
object was used throughout.

00:08:50.239 --> 00:08:54.960
This long code block demonstrates the idea of composability nicely.

00:08:54.960 --> 00:09:00.719
Try not to be drawn in to immediately understand it.

00:09:00.719 --> 00:09:05.200
Instead, notice how many smaller pieces of the Tidyverse are used to solve an overall

00:09:05.200 --> 00:09:07.320
more complex problem.

00:09:07.320 --> 00:09:11.559
In some instances, some functions such as mutate are used over and over again.

00:09:11.559 --> 00:09:16.520
The end result is we are able to solve complex problems more quickly.

00:09:16.520 --> 00:09:22.479
In this particular case, it allowed us to assess the vulnerability of different regions

00:09:22.479 --> 00:09:28.039
of the UK, split across different vulnerabilities of the vulnerability index.

00:09:28.039 --> 00:09:33.239
So let's turn back to Matt and find out how these design principles have impacted our

00:09:33.239 --> 00:09:35.840
response to the COVID-19 pandemic.

00:09:36.359 --> 00:09:40.559
Have you noticed how all the principles are linked together?

00:09:40.559 --> 00:09:45.799
The Tidyverse principles are rooted in cognitive theories of mind, and they make it easy for

00:09:45.799 --> 00:09:52.840
humans like me and Mike to pull insights out of datasets and make new tools for people.

00:09:52.840 --> 00:09:58.520
One example of how we've used our vulnerability index to design better services for people

00:09:58.520 --> 00:10:01.520
is our COVID-19 Hardship Fund.

00:10:01.719 --> 00:10:07.919
Aviva, an insurance company, donated £5 million to us to give to people who are facing economic

00:10:07.919 --> 00:10:10.679
hardship during the pandemic.

00:10:10.679 --> 00:10:15.320
We used our vulnerability index, alongside other research, to figure out that the people

00:10:15.320 --> 00:10:21.599
most likely to need financial support included those without access to state welfare, older

00:10:21.599 --> 00:10:27.359
isolated people, people facing homelessness or living in temporary accommodation, and

00:10:27.359 --> 00:10:31.080
survivors of gender-based violence.

00:10:31.080 --> 00:10:35.760
In one region of England, this mapping, combined with local intelligence from our

00:10:35.760 --> 00:10:41.119
frontline teams, led to more than half of referrals to our Hardship Fund coming from

00:10:41.119 --> 00:10:43.679
the most vulnerable areas.

00:10:43.679 --> 00:10:50.880
As of December 2020, we've helped more than 7,000 people with financial assistance.

00:10:50.880 --> 00:10:55.520
So following the Tidyverse design principles has made it faster for Mike and I and others

00:10:55.640 --> 00:11:01.960
to get our ideas out of our heads and translated into something useful in the real world.

00:11:01.960 --> 00:11:07.159
This cognitive speed is really key for us, working as a humanitarian organisation.

00:11:07.159 --> 00:11:11.960
To put a spin on the well-known Agile phrase, we need to move fast and save things.

00:11:11.960 --> 00:11:17.520
And we're not just working with one another, it's often said your most important collaborator

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:21.500
is yourself, six months down the line.

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:26.260
Even if you don't use the Tidyverse itself, we suggest using all four design principles

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:30.700
as inspiration for future package and code design.

00:11:30.700 --> 00:11:35.099
Writing code and packages in the future, think about cognitive performance, not only

00:11:35.099 --> 00:11:37.380
computational performance.

00:11:37.380 --> 00:11:41.059
For our work on the Vulnerability Index, this meant that there hasn't been a single time

00:11:41.059 --> 00:11:46.359
that Mike or I had to explain our code to one another, which is remarkable.

00:11:46.359 --> 00:11:51.179
We should often be writing code that is human-centric and designed around how people actually think

00:11:51.179 --> 00:11:52.380
and work.

00:11:52.380 --> 00:11:57.539
The key is to build tools and analyses faster for real-world impact.

00:11:57.539 --> 00:11:58.380
Thank you for listening.

